  <static seed="1331" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalExpressionAlgebraSkills/divideRationalExpressions40.pg">
    <statement><p>Simplify this expression, and if applicable, write the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{9y^{2}-49}{3y^{2}+16y+21}} \div ({7-3y}) =}</m> <fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>-\frac{1}{y+3}, y\ne 2.33333\hbox{ and }y\ne -2.33333</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{9y^{2}-49}{3y^{2}+16y+21}} \div {7-3y} 
      \amp = {\frac{9y^{2}-49}{3y^{2}+16y+21}} \div \frac{{7-3y}}{1} \\
      \amp = {\frac{9y^{2}-49}{3y^{2}+16y+21}} \cdot {\frac{1}{7-3y}} \\
      \amp =  \frac{{\left(3y+7\right)\mathopen{}\left(3y-7\right)}}{{\left(3y+7\right)\mathopen{}\left(y+3\right)}} \cdot \frac{{1}}{{-\left(3y-7\right)}} \\
      \amp = {-\frac{1}{y+3}, y\ne 2.33333\hbox{ and }y\ne -2.33333}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factors <m>3y+7</m> and <m>3y-7</m> were canceled, the domain condition lost during the simplification are <m>y \ne {{\frac{7}{3}}\; and \;-{\frac{7}{3}}}</m>.</p>
</solution>
